RESEARCH PARTICIPANT CONSENT FORM

IronHack: Creating Impact from Governmental Open Data (OD) 

Sabine Brunswicker 

Purdue University 

 

What is the purpose of this study? 

The purpose of this study is to evaluate how participants in governmental “open data” contests increase their innovation productivity. For the context of our study, “open data contests” refers to contests in which participants utilize datasets that have been released by Federal agencies to address problems that affect society at large. The Research Center on Open Digital Innovation (RCODI) at Purdue is sponsoring these contests (called IronHacks). You are being asked to participate to help us increase the practical understanding of participation in hacking competitions, which are 21-day contests in which individuals create web-applications and mash-ups that utilize open governmental data to solve a civic problem. We anticipate several hundred participants will take part in this series of contests. 

 

What will I do if I choose to be in this study? 

If you choose to take part in the study, you will be asked to log in to our contest platform and respond to the tasks of the contest, published on the platform. As specified in the technical instructions, each challenge has a dataset associated with it, but you are free to use a range of additional datasets from data.gov to create a mash-up application and embed in a website. We encourage you to use the provided platform to discuss and interact with others in an anonymous way, but it is not required. If you start a contest, and then decide that you no longer wish to participate, you are free to stop at any time. Participation in the challenges is voluntary, as is completion of the survey. 

Throughout the 21-day contest you are asked to submit your application at least 4 times. At the start of the contest, we will send you a short survey that asks about the tools and techniques that you used, and your experiences during the contest. We will also survey experts to evaluate the innovativeness of your solution. Overall winners from each competition will be selected using this expert feedback. At the end of the competition, there will be another short survey to gather your experiences throughout the competition. 

The data that we collect will include activity information from the platform, your solution (including the code), your survey responses, and expert evaluations. We will be using email to contact you regarding the survey, and for prize distribution. The surveys will be delivered via Qualtrics, which is an online survey site that is easily accessible from any modern web browser. This data will remain confidential, though winners will be announced in a public press release by RCODI. 

 

How long will I be in the study? 

This study will cover the length of approximately 21 days for the hack, but you are free to participate when it is convenient for you during that time period. The hacking activity is accompanied by a survey. There will be a short survey at the beginning of the hacking contest, and another short survey after the completion of the survey. It will take about 20 to 30 min to complete each survey

 

What are the possible risks or discomforts? 

There are minimal risks associated with participation in this study. Activities undertaken by participants are similar to those in most hackathons, and participation on the platform will be similar to participation on other online communities that are regularly used by millions of people. 

Risks for this particular research include time sensitive challenges, but hacks are strategically being scheduled over weekends to allow for minimal impact on your regular schedule. You work individually, minimizing the impact on those who dislike group work. We do not anticipate any physical, social, or legal risks to be associated with our research. 

 

Are there any potential benefits? 

You will gain exposure to hacking, application development and new innovation practices. We gain proficiency in developing useful open data applications that create real value for citizens. 

Because the challenges revolve around the use of governmental open data, solutions may have the potential to have positive effects for other citizens. Results from this study may be used to increase the effectiveness of Open Innovation efforts with governmental data, including Challenge.Gov and Data.Gov. 

 

Will I receive payment or other incentives? 

Following the challenge guidelines in hacking and open data contests, we will utilize an expert panel of raters to review the submissions, and will be offering cash prizes for the winning submissions in the categories: Best Solution ($500), Greatest Winning Spirit ($250), and Greatest Community Spirit; ($150) in the form of an Amazon gift card. You will not be receiving any additional payment. Just like any other hacking event, we will offer swag (t-shirts, mugs, stickers, etc.) to our study participants. Finally, we will offer extra credit as outlined below. 

 

Class Credit 

In addition to the abovementioned incentive, by participating in this study you are eligible for extra class credit, which shall not exceed 3% of your overall grade. This credit is contingent upon completion of the two short surveys and submitting a working web-application at the end of the 21-day period. 

 

Can I still receive credit if I do not take part in, or withdraw from this study? 

You can still receive the same amount of class credit if you do not participate in, or withdraw from this study. Participation is entirely voluntary. The alternative assignment will be a coding project that will have a similar format and timeline to the abovementioned hacking contest and will require you in advance of the project to propose your own project, receive approval from the faculty member teaching the class, and code in a language that you have not previously used. 

 

When will I receive the extra credit? 

You will receive extra credit after the conclusion of the contest and after the regular course grades have been determined. If you choose to do your own project (the alternative), you will receive extra credit upon completion of that project and after the regular course grades have been determined. 

 

Will information about me and my participation be kept confidential? 

The project's research records may be reviewed by the National Science Foundation and by departments at Purdue University responsible for regulatory and research oversight. 

Within the platform, your confidentiality will be maintained using a pseudonym system. Furthermore, no disclosure of names will be made possible through Qualtrics. Individual registration emails will be available only to the research team, and will be maintained on a secure database located on ITAP servers.

The platform and Qualtrics records will be stored on ITAP servers for at least 2 years, which is the intended duration of the Challenge Platform. You will be able to see submissions. 

We have no plans for the complete destruction of data or codes at this point in time. If the Challenge Platform is successful, we intend to wipe all user data at the end of our experiments, and release the platform as an open source solution for open innovation. Copies of data collected on the Challenge Platform and via survey will likely be required to be available in perpetuity for journal submissions, and will be anonymized before transmission. 


What are my rights if I take part in this study? 

Your participation in this study is voluntary. You may choose not to participate or, if you agree to participate, you can withdraw your participation at any time without penalty or loss of benefits to which you are otherwise entitled. 


Who can I contact if I have questions about the study? 

If you have questions, comments or concerns about this research project, you can talk to one of the researchers: Professor Sabine Brunswicker (765.494.2885) 

If you have questions about your rights while taking part in the study or have concerns about the treatment of research participants, please call the Human Research Protection Program at (765) 494-5942, email (irb@purdue.edu)or write to: 

Human Research Protection Program - Purdue University 

Ernest C. Young Hall, Room 1032 

155 S. Grant St., 

West Lafayette, IN 47907-2114
